{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-haiku-4-5-20251001","id":"msg_01QmwrHZ9LXBeS4DeKCXcwRT","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01Jh5GxwReGZ3kgXz4cuVvH1","name":"StructuredOutput","input":{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"The primary translator produces a grammatically coherent translation that preserves the meaning of the source text, not just a word-for-word substitution.","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"Testing whether the neural translation API actually produces coherent output requires calling the real model. A mock could return any string (coherent or not), missing real failures like corrupted model weights, misconfigured API endpoints, or the model fine-tuned on bad data. Outcomes vary non-deterministically with neural models—different runs may produce different translations. Only the real API catches whether the model actually produces valid, meaning-preserving translations.","test_description":"Call the real neural translation API with standard test phrases (e.g., 'Hello, how are you?' in language A). Capture the output translation in language B and verify semantic preservation and grammatical coherence using automated similarity scoring (embedding-based comparison to gold references) or human review. Run multiple times to detect non-deterministic failures.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":"Test explicitly requires real neural API because grammatical coherence cannot be verified from a mock that claims correctness without proving it.","level_probabilities":{"Unit":0,"Integration":0.05,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0.85,"Workflow":0.05}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"When the translation API returns a 503 error, the service transparently falls back to the dictionary-based translator without returning an error to the caller.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Testing 'transparent fallback' requires verifying both error detection AND that the fallback actually returns a valid result to the caller. A unit test with mocked API and mocked fallback would pass even if: (a) the service calls fallback but then returns an error anyway, (b) the fallback is never invoked due to error-handling bugs, (c) the service returns an invalid or partial result. To catch these, the fallback (accessing SQLite) must be real or a realistic test double that actually queries the database. This requires integration of the error-handling logic with the real fallback translator.","test_description":"Create a test with mock neural translation API configured to return 503. Provide a real SQLite test database with known phrase-translation pairs. Call the service with a source text matching a phrase in the database. Verify: (1) response is success (not error), (2) response contains a translation (from fallback), (3) translation matches expected fallback result, (4) no error is reported to caller.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":"Test requires both mocked error response (mock API) and real fallback execution (real SQLite + translator), which is integration-level.","level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.2,"Integration":0.7,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0.05}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"The dictionary-based fallback returns the correct pre-stored translation for phrases that exist in the SQLite database.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Correctness requires the fallback translator to actually query SQLite and retrieve the correct value. Mocking the database would miss: schema mismatches, incorrect SQL query logic (wrong table/column names, malformed WHERE clauses), parsing errors when extracting results, case sensitivity or encoding bugs, index issues, or transactions failing. A unit test with a mocked database query passes even if the actual SQL query is broken or the schema doesn't match. Real database interaction is needed to verify end-to-end correctness.","test_description":"Create a test SQLite database with known phrase-translation pairs (e.g., 'hello' → 'hola'). Call the fallback translator with each phrase and verify: (1) returned translation matches stored value exactly, (2) phrases not in database return null/default (not error or random value), (3) case sensitivity is handled correctly ('Hello' vs 'hello'), (4) special characters and accents are preserved, (5) encoded strings are decoded correctly.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":"Test requires real database interaction; a mock would not catch query logic errors or schema mismatches.","level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.05,"Integration":0.9,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"The quality tracking comparison correctly computes edit distance between primary and fallback outputs and stores the metric.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"This tests two components working together: edit distance computation (testable in unit tests) and metric storage (requires real I/O). A unit test with mocked storage would pass even if: (a) metrics are never persisted to the database, (b) the persistence call fails silently, (c) the storage schema is incompatible or the value is truncated, (d) concurrent writes corrupt stored metrics. To catch these, the service must actually write to a database or log file and the test must verify the value persists correctly. Integration testing with real storage is required.","test_description":"Provide mock primary translator returning 'hello' and mock fallback returning 'hallo'. Call the service to compute quality metrics when both are available. Verify: (1) edit distance is computed correctly (distance should be 1), (2) metric is actually stored in database/log (not just mocked as called), (3) retrieved metrics match computed values, (4) metrics include correct timestamps and source metadata, (5) multiple metrics can be stored without overwriting.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":"Test requires real storage persistence to verify metrics are actually saved; mocks would not catch storage failures.","level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.1,"Integration":0.8,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0.05}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"When both translators are available, the service returns the primary translation and logs the quality comparison in the background.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"This tests coordination of three components: (1) returning primary translation synchronously, (2) initiating background logging asynchronously, (3) ensuring they don't block or interfere. A unit test with mocked logger and mocked translators would pass even if: (a) background logging is never actually started (runs synchronously instead), (b) logging completes but crashes before persisting, (c) the response is returned before async setup completes, causing logging to fail, (d) the response returns the fallback instead of primary. Real async/background infrastructure is needed to verify logging truly runs in the background without blocking the response. This requires integration testing.","test_description":"Provide mock primary translator returning 'hello' and mock fallback returning 'hola'. Call the service with both available. Verify: (1) response immediately returns primary translation ('hello', not 'hola'), (2) quality comparison is logged asynchronously (assert logger was called or log file was written), (3) response is returned without waiting for logging to complete (test with deliberately slow mock logger), (4) background logging eventual completes and persists. Use async test infrastructure (pytest-asyncio) to properly capture and verify async logging behavior.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":"Test requires real async coordination and logging, not just synchronous mocks; mocks would not catch timing issues or background execution failures.","level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.1,"Integration":0.7,"System":0.1,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0.1}}]},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reaso